WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:26.260
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Good morning,
everyone, and thank you all

00:00:26.260 --> 00:00:29.960
for coming despite the bad weather.

00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:34.190
I'm delighted to see you all here
for this very special program

00:00:34.190 --> 00:00:39.800
to celebrate with us the gift by
the Afghan Media Resource Center

00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:41.590
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:48.050
It gives a unique digital
archive of 94,650 photographs,

00:00:48.050 --> 00:00:55.280
1,200 hours of videos, 350 hours
of audio recordings on Afghanistan.

00:00:55.280 --> 00:00:58.420
That's the largest --
the largest collection

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:01.480
of its kind anywhere in the world.

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:06.670 position:56%
We're here today to recognize the
work that was done by so many people

00:01:06.670 --> 00:01:11.770
in Afghanistan and in Washington,
D.C. I'm Mary-Jane Deeb,

00:01:11.770 --> 00:01:15.120 position:56%
Chief of the African and Middle
Eastern Division here at the Library

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:18.620
of Congress, and I will be your
host for the rest of the program.

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:23.650 position:56%
For the sake of time, I will
introduce each speaker very briefly,

00:01:23.650 --> 00:01:28.400 position:56%
and have put on your seats their
fuller bios, so you have their bios,

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:33.560
so you can have a better
idea of who each person is.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:38.320
Throughout the presentation we
will have a slideshow of some

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:42.610
of the images from the archive
that illustrate the wide range

00:01:42.610 --> 00:01:48.420
of subjects that are covered
by this 30 year-long project.

00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:52.720
I will now begin by calling on
the acting Librarian of Congress,

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:56.360
David Mao, would directs the
operations of the Library

00:01:56.360 --> 00:02:01.350
of Congress and overseas this
entire library, which is,

00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:04.870
as many of you know, the
largest library in the world.

00:02:04.870 --> 00:02:08.530
He oversees its various
units to ensure

00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:12.950
that the library services the
Congress, the American people,

00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:15.460
and the world are provide
effectively.

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:16.760
So, David.

00:02:21.050 --> 00:02:22.350
&gt;&gt; David S. Mao: Thank
you very much, Mary-Jane,

00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:23.650
and good morning to all of you.

00:02:23.650 --> 00:02:26.820
As Mary-Jane mentioned, my name is
David Mao and I have the privilege

00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:29.620
of serving as the acting librarian.

00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:33.630 position:56%
I am very, very honored to be able
to welcome all of you to the Library

00:02:33.630 --> 00:02:36.930
of Congress here today so that we
can celebrate this very important

00:02:36.930 --> 00:02:41.380
project and learn more about the
project, a product of cooperation

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:44.990
between the Afghan Media
Resource Center in Kabul

00:02:44.990 --> 00:02:47.470
and various U.S. government
agencies,

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:50.010
including the United
States Department of State

00:02:50.010 --> 00:02:52.200
and the Library of Congress.

00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:55.990
As you can see on the
slides on either side,

00:02:55.990 --> 00:02:58.330
the cooperation has
produced unique photos.

00:02:58.330 --> 00:03:03.100
There is also video and audio
digital archives in these archive

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:09.200
on Afghanistan covering the
period from 1987 to 2012.

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:13.260
We now at the Library of
Congress hold the digital copies

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:16.680
of that archive and we will
eventually make it available

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:19.770
to the public through
our reading rooms.

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:21.400
Over the next hour
or so you will hear

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:23.880
from these distinguished
speakers here are the at --

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:27.970
at the table talking about
how this project came about

00:03:27.970 --> 00:03:32.410
and really what does this
archive mean to the world.

00:03:32.410 --> 00:03:35.520
Just a little bit of
information, we are here in the --

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:37.010
what's known as the
Northeast Pavilion,

00:03:37.010 --> 00:03:40.120
or the Government Pavilion
here at the Library of Congress

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:42.650
in the historic Thomas
Jefferson building.

00:03:42.650 --> 00:03:46.950 position:56%
And, as you can see, there are lots
of symbols that represent this room,

00:03:46.950 --> 00:03:50.650
the government of the United
States, the government itself

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:54.180
in the medallion on the -- on the
ceiling and the representations

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:56.730
around the wall of the
different regions of our country,

00:03:56.730 --> 00:03:59.530
as well as different
executive branch agencies

00:03:59.530 --> 00:04:02.850
within the United States,
at least at the time

00:04:02.850 --> 00:04:04.440
that this building was created.

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:07.630
So you will see representations of
the treasuring State Department,

00:04:07.630 --> 00:04:10.380
Justice and Post Office
Departments, Agriculture

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:13.230
and Interior, War and Navy.

00:04:13.230 --> 00:04:17.740
And I think in a way that these
representations symbolize very well

00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:21.380
the Afghan Media Resource Center
collection here at the Library

00:04:21.380 --> 00:04:24.440
of Congress, because these
themes that are represented

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:28.170
on these walls can also be seen
in these digital representations,

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:29.470
whether it be in the pictures

00:04:29.470 --> 00:04:32.920
or in the audio visual
materials in the collection.

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:35.370
They talk about different
regions in the area.

00:04:35.370 --> 00:04:37.080
They talk about different
things that happened,

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:40.980
whether it's sharing a meal
together or negotiation,

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:45.240
whether it's building or
destruction, whether it's dying

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:48.500
or planting and enjoying
bountiful harvest.

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:52.240
These are all represented by the
different areas in our country

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:56.630
and in the different symbols of the
departments that we represent here.

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:59.690 position:56%
So I think it's particularly fitting
that we're in this room to be able

00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:02.460
to talk about this collection.

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:06.760 position:56%
So with that said I'm very glad that
all of you are here today to hear

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:10.410
about this very special gift,
and to hear from those folks

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:13.790
who have been instrumental
in making this all happen.

00:05:13.790 --> 00:05:16.900
I know you'll really enjoy
hearing about the archives,

00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:20.280
the story about its creation,
and the way it came about.

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:25.150
And I hope it will inspire
you to come and learn more

00:05:25.150 --> 00:05:28.980
about the Library of Congress, not
only to use these materials to look

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:33.200
at them, but also to look at them
for research, and also perhaps

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:35.990
to look at more of the materials
here in the collection of Library

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:39.720
of Congress from around the
world that are preserved here

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.760
and can be used for all of you.

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:45.100
So with that I want to thank
you again and welcome you

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:55.390
to the Library of Congress
[applause].

00:05:55.390 --> 00:05:57.540
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb: Thank
you, thank you so much.

00:05:57.540 --> 00:05:58.840
Thank you.

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:00.140
Well, thank you, thank you, David.

00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:06.580
He has an extremely busy schedule
and he has come especially to be

00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:11.260
with us today, so we
really appreciate this.

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:17.760
And before I introduce our
speakers, I would like to recognize

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:24.620
and thank some of the people
who made this project possible.

00:06:24.620 --> 00:06:28.130
First, I would like to thank
the Afghan Media Resource Center

00:06:28.130 --> 00:06:34.130
and its director, Haji Sayed
Daud, who is with us today,

00:06:34.130 --> 00:06:38.400
and all the MRC staff who have
produced the original photos

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:42.330
and videos and then
organized, archived,

00:06:42.330 --> 00:06:47.000
and stored these materials,
and later worked tirelessly

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:52.150
to produce the metadata in
Pashto, Darti [phonetic], English,

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:56.940
as well as in translation
and in transliteration.

00:06:56.940 --> 00:07:00.370
That transliteration is
a complex library system

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:04.590
that transcribes phonetically
various scripts, in this case Darti

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:08.560
and Pashto, into Roman
script, without which,

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:11.680
without this metadata this
collection could not have been

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:15.090 position:56%
absorbed by the Library of Congress.

00:07:15.090 --> 00:07:20.370
Haji Daud is an extraordinary
man, who has dedicated his life

00:07:20.370 --> 00:07:25.360
to recording in photos and
videos the history of Afghanistan

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:27.510
in the last three decades.

00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:31.980
He has created the single,
most important record

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:38.190 position:56%
of Afghan contemporary history and
society in existence anywhere today.

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:42.270
He has accomplished this feat
by training Afghan journalists,

00:07:42.270 --> 00:07:47.910
whom he has sent to every region
of Afghanistan to film, videotape,

00:07:47.910 --> 00:07:53.200
record, and photograph the
lives of ordinary Afghans.

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:57.540
And as the librarian said,
in war and peace, in planting

00:07:57.540 --> 00:08:02.220
and harvesting, in
negotiation and in fighting,

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:04.260
in bringing up children, in caring

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:07.470
for the living, and
caring for the dead.

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:12.220
He has risked his life many
times so that this unique record

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:15.190
of Afghanistan's history
is preserved,

00:08:15.190 --> 00:08:18.290
and so that the world becomes
aware of what the people

00:08:18.290 --> 00:08:21.650
of Afghanistan have been through
in the last three decades.

00:08:21.650 --> 00:08:26.770
In my mind he's a hero who has
brought his life's work to us here

00:08:26.770 --> 00:08:30.440
at the library so that we
can store and preserve it

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:34.800 position:56%
and make it available to scholars
and researchers, and to all who want

00:08:34.800 --> 00:08:38.550
to know more about Afghanistan.

00:08:38.550 --> 00:08:44.160
Having said this, I move on
to the speakers and I would

00:08:44.160 --> 00:08:48.200
like to thank the Department
of State, here presented

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:52.740
by U.S. Ambassador Peter Tomsen,
who has been a tireless supporter

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:58.520
