00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:22.180
The AMRC's coverage of
the Afghan wars began

00:18:22.180 --> 00:18:26.200
in 1986 and ended in 2012.

00:18:26.200 --> 00:18:30.980
75% of the archive, the
heart of the collection,

00:18:30.980 --> 00:18:35.750
focuses on the nine year, blood
soaked, Soviet Afghan war,

00:18:35.750 --> 00:18:37.960
during which a million
Afghans perished,

00:18:37.960 --> 00:18:42.440
plus the three additional years
it took for the Mujahideen

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:46.600
to overthrow the Soviet
sponsored Najib regime.

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:51.120 position:56%
The archive contains many
thousands of news items brought back

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:56.140
by AMRC media teams from
inside Afghanistan during the

00:18:56.140 --> 00:18:58.150
Soviet occupation.

00:18:58.150 --> 00:19:03.120
As David Isby [assumed spelling]
mentioned, had Afghan eyes

00:19:03.120 --> 00:19:10.700
on the war and reported it through
the AMRC Afghan Institution,

00:19:10.700 --> 00:19:16.640
which was devoted in Peshawar
to tracking the Afghan war.

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:21.460
The news reports -- their news
reports portrayed the desperate

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:24.950
fighting and the valiant
spirit of the Afghan people.

00:19:24.950 --> 00:19:30.170
The teams gave their microphones to
Afghans, villages, elders, women,

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:34.680 position:56%
children, Afghan commanders, and
their Mujahideen inside the country,

00:19:34.680 --> 00:19:38.310
allowing them to speak directly
to a worldwide ordinance.

00:19:38.310 --> 00:19:42.150
The archive also carries
reports from Pakistan,

00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:46.550 position:56%
from the refugee camps, from various
presenting Mujahideen headquarters,

00:19:46.550 --> 00:19:50.400
from diplomats, and foreign
embassies, and consulates

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:54.980
that were watching and
reporting on the Afghan war.

00:19:54.980 --> 00:20:00.690
I met with Haji Daud and his AMRC
office on every visit to Peshawar.

00:20:00.690 --> 00:20:03.970
It was completely an
Afghan operation.

00:20:03.970 --> 00:20:08.090
An AK-47 leaned on his
bed in a corner room,

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:11.920
attesting to the dangers
that he faced every day.

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:14.990
No foreigners were
present, only Afghans.

00:20:14.990 --> 00:20:18.940
They were all young,
dedicated and well-trained.

00:20:18.940 --> 00:20:24.210
When not editing film or processing
photos, they were going back

00:20:24.210 --> 00:20:26.110
and forth into Afghanistan,

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:30.230
operating out of Mujahideen
areas sometimes for weeks,

00:20:30.230 --> 00:20:34.220
sometimes for months,
bringing windows on the war

00:20:34.220 --> 00:20:40.030
in every Afghan region to
audiences around the globe.

00:20:40.030 --> 00:20:44.000
Let's now pause for a
moment, if you will,

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:48.670
to ponder why the AMRC
archive built by Haji Daud

00:20:48.670 --> 00:20:52.460
and his AMRC journalists
is so unique,

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:56.510
and indeed so historically
important.

00:20:56.510 --> 00:20:59.570
In large part the answer
lies in the relative paucity

00:20:59.570 --> 00:21:05.630
of reliable reportage the war
following the 1979 Soviet invasion.

00:21:05.630 --> 00:21:08.210
In the U.S., and internationally,

00:21:08.210 --> 00:21:13.010
it is easy to access the prolific
media coverage of World War II,

00:21:13.010 --> 00:21:15.940
the Korean War, the Vietnam War,

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:21.320
not to mention the post-9/11
wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:26.580
But there is a huge gap, almost I
would say a blank space regarding

00:21:26.580 --> 00:21:30.250
on the ground coverage
of the Soviet Afghan war.

00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:34.870
Some of you in this room made
it past Pakistani border guards

00:21:34.870 --> 00:21:38.240
and Soviet outposts to
report on the fighting,

00:21:38.240 --> 00:21:42.650
but not many Western journals and
cameramen were able to venture

00:21:42.650 --> 00:21:47.220
for long periods inside
most of Afghanistan.

00:21:47.220 --> 00:21:51.520
Soviet propaganda, of course, was
bountiful throughout this period,

00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:54.430
but it delivered a false
and cynical narrative

00:21:54.430 --> 00:21:58.520
of the true situation
inside the country.

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:04.250
The vast, usually originally
sourced AMRC archive now housed

00:22:04.250 --> 00:22:10.170
in the Library of Congress will
fill this nearly blank space.

00:22:10.170 --> 00:22:13.310
For the decades to come it will
be the most authentic source

00:22:13.310 --> 00:22:17.210
for anyone, anywhere,
seeking accurate information

00:22:17.210 --> 00:22:21.600
on the Soviet Afghan war to include
historians, scholars, authors,

00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:26.280
policymakers inside and outside
governments, members of the media,

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:31.060
the military, diplomats,
and politicians.

00:22:31.060 --> 00:22:36.220 position:56%
And the archive's importance does
not end, as Haji Daud will tell you,

00:22:36.220 --> 00:22:42.030
with the Soviet [inaudible]
Najib regime's overthrow in 1992.

00:22:42.030 --> 00:22:44.700
For in the global and
strategic context,

00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:50.120
