and lots of work to do.

00:48:56.530 --> 00:48:58.710
Haji, Nick, and I tried
to spend time

00:48:58.710 --> 00:49:02.220 position:56%
with the cameramen before they left,
reminding them that in addition

00:49:02.220 --> 00:49:05.570
to generating the combat
related footage and stories,

00:49:05.570 --> 00:49:08.120
which was their primarily
assignment,

00:49:08.120 --> 00:49:13.240
to also document Afghan cultural
life, wedding, Nowruz celebrations,

00:49:13.240 --> 00:49:18.550
New Year celebrations, children,
families, and other social events.

00:49:18.550 --> 00:49:23.650
It should be mentioned that this
war was called the Hidden War

00:49:23.650 --> 00:49:26.690
because for years virtually no
Western journalists were willing

00:49:26.690 --> 00:49:30.170
to take the risks to go
deeply into Afghanistan.

00:49:30.170 --> 00:49:32.450
As Haji mentioned, there
were no reports coming

00:49:32.450 --> 00:49:36.560
from central Afghanistan or from
the far west or the far north,

00:49:36.560 --> 00:49:39.170
where it would require often nine,

00:49:39.170 --> 00:49:43.490
10 days of travel to
reach the location.

00:49:43.490 --> 00:49:46.100
So for the next year and a
half under Haji's direction,

00:49:46.100 --> 00:49:50.130
AMRC dispatched over 100 two
to three men crews to all parts

00:49:50.130 --> 00:49:53.850
of Afghanistan, mostly to
places with no electricity,

00:49:53.850 --> 00:49:58.810
no battery chargers, no
phone service, and no roads.

00:49:58.810 --> 00:50:03.110 position:56%
Our AMRC news teams sometimes
delayed for weeks due to bad weather

00:50:03.110 --> 00:50:06.900 position:56%
or being detained by local warlords,
who would eventually return

00:50:06.900 --> 00:50:09.280
to [inaudible] and sit
down with our editors

00:50:09.280 --> 00:50:13.230
to create our weekly AMRC news
reports, which we would then rush

00:50:13.230 --> 00:50:19.210
to send via DHL to syndication
services in London, like Viz News,

00:50:19.210 --> 00:50:20.890
which is the parent
company of [inaudible].

00:50:20.890 --> 00:50:24.770
These services would check
our stories for accuracy

00:50:24.770 --> 00:50:28.880
and professionalism and then
feed weekly AMRC stories

00:50:28.880 --> 00:50:34.650
to over 245 broadcasters in
over 100 countries worldwide.

00:50:34.650 --> 00:50:37.010
Meanwhile, AMRC photos
were being distributed

00:50:37.010 --> 00:50:39.950
through Sigma, Black Star, and AFP.

00:50:39.950 --> 00:50:45.110
The AMRC was starting to
achieve some of its goals.

00:50:45.110 --> 00:50:48.480
Then on December 31,
'87, Boston University

00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:52.350
and Dean [inaudible] were
suddenly phased out of the project.

00:50:52.350 --> 00:50:56.750
As Boston left I agreed to stay
on as the senior media advisor,

00:50:56.750 --> 00:51:01.290 position:56%
now to an AMRC that was finally
independent, run totally by Afghans,

00:51:01.290 --> 00:51:06.310
with no American bosses
or supervision.

00:51:06.310 --> 00:51:09.750
Then after setting up the
international distribution,

00:51:09.750 --> 00:51:13.490
I was able to do as the British
say, make myself redundant

00:51:13.490 --> 00:51:17.290
and leave the project
totally to Haji and his staff,

00:51:17.290 --> 00:51:21.600
which was a shared dream of Nick
Mills and mine from the beginning,

00:51:21.600 --> 00:51:27.830
that we should phase ourselves
out of this as soon as possible.

00:51:27.830 --> 00:51:31.240
Peter Tomsen, Ambassador Tomsen
did a wonderful job describing the

00:51:31.240 --> 00:51:33.500
significance of the project.

00:51:33.500 --> 00:51:38.940
What I would only like to add is
I think the AMRC was finally able

00:51:38.940 --> 00:51:42.620
to open a window on this hidden
war and generate news reports

00:51:42.620 --> 00:51:48.430
and documentation from 25 of
Afghanistan's then 29 provinces,

00:51:48.430 --> 00:51:51.020
reports that made an
impact on viewers

00:51:51.020 --> 00:51:53.500
and governments throughout
the world.

00:51:53.500 --> 00:51:56.050
In the process, more than
20 of our journalists

00:51:56.050 --> 00:51:58.990
and cameramen were injured,
and two of our cameramen,

00:51:58.990 --> 00:52:04.020
[inaudible] were killed while
on assignment for the AMRC.

00:52:04.020 --> 00:52:14.100
Nick Mills says the best thing he
did for the AMRC was to find me,

00:52:14.100 --> 00:52:16.930
